snippet.title: #NABI2019: STEM Challenges as Broader Impacts Programs
snippet.description:
Matt Johnson, Kathleen Hill, Amber Cesare, and Gabe Knowles, Penn State University presented at #NABI2019 on how to use STEM challenges for K‚Äì12 students as an excellent format for broader impacts.

They can promote participation in STEM of those populations that are typically underrepresented, can improve STEM education, and can increase public engagement with science and technology. Further, a well-established program that becomes sustainable can be used in broader impacts programs of future proposals in related fields. However, these programs can be difficult to develop, time-consuming to implement, and challenging to attract a large number of participants. The purpose of this session is twofold. First, we will use two examples of STEM challenges we host at the Center for Science and the Schools (CSATS) at Penn State to illustrate some of the obstacles and solutions we have found in the development and implementation of these programs. Second, we will begin to form an affinity group of BI professionals involved or interested in this style of BI program.

snippet.title: Building the gripper for the robot arm (Dynamixel + Amber)
snippet.description:
Today we have build the gripper for the 7 axis robotic arm (Amber B1). But it should be useful also for other robot arms. The gripper uses torque control and torque based position control, which make this gripper ideal for fragile light objects as well as for heavy objects. All this is possible thanks to Dynamixel servo.

snippet.title: Amber Electric's SmartShift‚Ñ¢
snippet.description:
Dr. Sarah Russell-Smith, 12 May 2021. 

SmartShift‚Ñ¢ makes home appliances and batteries smarter.

Amber is an innovative Aussie energy company giving households access to the real-time wholesale price of electricity. Customers can make additional savings on power bills by using power at times when it's cheaper and greener, and using less when it's expensive and fossil-fueled.

Our new beta product, SmartShift‚Ñ¢, puts these cheaper and greener savings on autopilot. It's technology that optimises everyday home devices (such as electric hot water systems, pool pumps, and household batteries) to lower energy bills. This means a cheaper Amber bill for customers, and greater demand for renewable energy in Australia.

In mid-2020 we began trialling SmartShift‚Ñ¢ with eligible customers in South Australia, with support from the SA government. We plan to make SmartShift‚Ñ¢ available in other states soon. The focus of this talk will be to share the initial results of SmartShift‚Ñ¢ trial.

This webinar is the final in a series of eight webinars on consumer-centric energy, being held between October 2020 and May 2021, co-hosted by the Energy Transition Hub and the Climate and Energy College, sponsored by the Victorian Clean Technology Fund.

snippet.title: The Impact of Algorithms On Competition: The Prevention and The Cure
snippet.description:
Seminar by Amber Darr at the UCL Centre for AI. Recorded on the 22nd July 2020.

Abstract:
Why should a person interested in Artificial Intelligence, care about competition law? To begin a conversation on this topic, consider how increasing digitalisation has revolutionised not only the marketplace and the way economic actors operate but also consumer experience. However, are developments in this regard always positive? For instance, do digital markets allow for greater transparency and symmetric dissemination of information? Can new actors enter the marketplace easily and expand without any significant hurdles? Assume, for today, that the answer to both these questions is yes. That is, start from the premise that no one player dominates the market and the risk of concentration of power in the hands of one player is reduced. This suggests that digital markets and platforms are largely beneficial for their customers in that they offer them lower prices and greater choice, that is, they increase "consumer welfare," the keystone of current competition policy and market regulation. However, the reality is somewhat more complicated due to digital markets increasingly utilising a range of algorithms which whilst increase transparency in the market, also allow for overt or tacit collusion amongst market competitors which has an adverse impact on competition in the market and on consumer welfare. This paper questions whether given the wide ranging impact of computer generated algorithms, it may be appropriate for competition law to recognise and treat computers as independent market actors and subjects of competition law in their own right; it examines actions of the computers -- algorithms -- that may properly be examined under competition law and explores possible regulation which will not only sanction anti-competitive algorithmic collusion but will also ensure that artificial intelligence/machine learning is, at the very least, trustworthy, legal, ethical and robust. More broadly, it considers how granting "civil rights" and/or "legal personhood" to an autonomous system such as a robot or an artificial intelligence product, may alter this picture.
 
Bio: Amber Darr is a Lecturer in Law at Coventry University and a Senior Research Fellow at the UCL Centre for Law, Economics and Society. She holds a PhD in Law from University College London and is also a Barrister of Lincoln‚Äôs Inn and an Advocate of the Supreme Court of Pakistan. She may be reached at amber.darr@ucl.ac.uk. Additional information about her can be found at: 
https://www.ucl.ac.uk/cles/amber-darr and https://pureportal.coventry.ac.uk/en/persons/amber-darr

snippet.title: Nowy Styl Smart Chair uses Gemsense RED AMBER sensor IoT platform
snippet.description: Jonathan Schipper of Gemsense shows their Smart Chair made in partnership with Nowy Styl of Poland. They have integrated 14 sensors into the office chair, motion sensors, Gyroscope, Magnetometer, temperature, humidity and more. It can be used to expand the VR gaming experience. Gemsense partners with DSP Group to use their Ultra-Low Energy (ULE) System-on-Chips (SoCs) wireless chipset solutions to power the new Navigo Smart connected chair by Nowy Styl Group, maker of furniture solutions for office and public spaces. The Navigo Smart chair is further enhanced by the RED AMBER sensor IoT platform by Gemsense. You can also watch the interview filmed by AndroidAuthority here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zIDRt_ul4aM
